{[show NESW]
[ROLE leader][STAGE pre-lead] Lead the \S2, fourth-best from your longest suit — the standard attack against 3NT.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE auction-end] You are in 3NT needing nine tricks. Count the top winners: three hearts, three clubs, the \SA — seven. The diamonds are shaky and the defense will have the ace. The extra tricks must come from spades, where your \SQ-J-6-4 faces dummy's A-9-3. Now for this lesson's idea: the finesse cards in that suit are not just the queen and jack — look hard at dummy's NINE. If the ten sits with West, the nine is as good as a royal. Listen to the opening lead; it may tell you exactly that.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-lead] The \S2 — fourth-best — and East's seven forces only your jack. Trick one is a gift, but the real prize is the information: a fourth-best lead promises length with strength, so West holds the king AND the ten. So play a second spade toward dummy and calmly insert the NINE — it wins, West's ten helpless underneath it. The ace makes three spade tricks, and with the hearts and clubs cashing that is nine. West's king takes its trick in the end, but the ten never does.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-play] The deep finesse: leading toward A-9-x and playing the NINE, because the lead had marked the ten on your left. The nine and ten win tricks for whoever respects them — and the opening lead is evidence, every bit as loud as the bidding. You read it, you went deep, and the ninth trick appeared out of a three of spades.}
