{[show NESW]
[ROLE leader][STAGE pre-lead] Lead the \CK, top of your \CK-Q-T sequence — the solid start against the diamond game.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE auction-end] East preempted 3\H and you bought it in 4\D — ten tricks. Trumps will supply six, the \HA and \CA make eight, and the last two must come out of spades: dummy's Q-T-6-3-2 opposite your K-8-4, missing the ace, jack, nine, seven, five. Now count the OTHER hand: East showed seven hearts, so the missing spade strength is bunched with West. If West holds ace AND jack over dummy's queen, leading the queen is hopeless — it loses to the ace and promotes nothing. Look one card deeper.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-lead] West led the \CK to dummy's ace. Draw trumps — East's jack falls — and now the spade suit, the deep way: lead LOW from your hand, and when West plays low, insert dummy's TEN. It holds! West's jack sat over the queen but under the ten's cheek — with the ace-jack both marked on your left, the ten was the only card in dummy that could win a cheap trick. Later your king scores, West's ace takes its due, and ten tricks are home.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-play] Vacant spaces plus a deep finesse: seven hearts with East meant the spade honors lived with West, so the QUEEN was doomed but the TEN was promoted to a finesse card. The machine that played this deal first went one down banging honors; the deep ten made it. When the top cards are marked against you, count downward — somewhere in the spot cards there is usually one that can still be led through the guard.}
