{[show NESW]
[ROLE leader][STAGE pre-lead] Lead the \DQ, top of your \DQ-J doubleton — a safe, solid start against the spade game.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE auction-end] You are in 4\S after East showed the minors, needing ten tricks. The hand turns on the trump suit: your \SA-T-8-4-3 opposite dummy's K-J-6 — an EIGHT-card fit missing the queen. Here is the arithmetic that decides it: with eight cards, the defenders hold five, and the queen usually sits with three of them — too deep to drop under your ace and king. The old rule says it plainly: EIGHT EVER. With eight cards, take the finesse.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-lead] West led the \DQ to your ace. Trumps at once, and by the rule: lead low toward dummy and insert the JACK — it wins, West playing low from his queen. Cash the ace next; the queen still does not fall (she started with two guards, exactly as the odds warned), but she is trapped: dummy's king sits over her, and she never takes a trick. Set up the clubs, concede your red-suit losers, ten tricks.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-play] Eight ever: with an eight-card fit missing the queen, the finesse is the percentage play, and banging the ace-king would have crowned West's guarded queen a winner. Notice the two halves of the rule working together — the hook won a trick AND the king stayed over her afterward. Remember the other half of the rhyme; it arrives on the next board.}
