[ROLE leader][STAGE pre-lead] Lead the \CA, top of your \CA-K — take your club tricks while you look at dummy.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE auction-end] You are in 4\H needing ten tricks, and again the question sits in trumps: \HA-K-9-7-5-3 opposite J-4-2 — but count the fit this time. NINE cards, not eight. Now the defenders hold only four, the queen is usually alone or with one guard, and the arithmetic flips: cashing the ace and king catches her more often than the finesse does. NINE NEVER. And look closer — here the hook would not merely be inferior, it points the WRONG way.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-lead] West cashes both top clubs and the defense takes its diamond ace — three tricks, their full ration. Win the return, and play trumps by the rule: the KING, then the ACE — and East's queen, doubleton all along, falls under the second round. No guess, no hook, no drama. Had you led toward the jack instead, West would have covered it for a trump trick out of thin air. Draw the last trump and claim ten.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-play] Nine never: with nine cards missing the queen, play the tops — the drop is the percentage line, and on this deal the tempting jack-finesse would have LOST outright, the queen sitting behind the jack. Yesterday's tool is not today's tool; the fit count, not the habit, chooses the play. Eight ever, nine never — half a rhyme each way.}
