[ROLE leader][STAGE pre-lead] Lead the \SJ, top of your \SJ-T sequence — the safe choice against the grand slam.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE auction-end] Partner has put you in 7\H — thirteen tricks, no losers allowed, no second chances. The clubs will run, the diamonds sit under your ace-queen, and everything reduces to the trump suit: \HA-K-5-3-2 in dummy opposite your J-9-8-4, missing the queen. A finesse toward your jack EXISTS. In a grand slam, with a NINE-card fit, do not touch it. Nine never — and never more never than at the seven level.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-lead] Win the spade in dummy and go straight at trumps by the arithmetic: the KING — West's ten drops — then the ACE — and West's queen falls with it. Q-T doubleton, exactly what nine-card odds promised. The rest is a procession: the diamonds behind the ace-queen-jack, the club suit, the spade king. Thirteen tricks, and notice with a shudder: a first-round finesse toward the jack would have lost to that queen, and the grand with it.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-play] The whole rule in one deal: nine cards, missing queen, cash the tops — she came down in two rounds, while the "clever" finesse was a 2200-point mistake sitting one card away. The deeper your contract, the more the arithmetic outranks the flourish. Eight ever, nine never; in a grand, carve it in stone.}
